Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @Potatoes{450%grams} into 1cm chunks (no need to peel). Halve any large
@Cauliflower Florets{300%grams}.

Pop the potatoes onto one side of a large #baking tray{}. Place the cauliflower
florets onto the other side. Drizzle with @oil{}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{},
then sprinkle the @Curry Powder Mix{1%sachet} over both veg.

Toss to coat, then spread out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{18-20%minutes}.
Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @Onion{1}(halved, peeled and chopped) into
small pieces.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #saucepan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @Diced British Chicken Breast{240%grams}(diced) and onion and
stir-fry until browned, ~{4-5%minutes}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and utensils after handling raw meat.

In the meantime, peel and grate the @Garlic Clove{3}(peeled and grated) (or use
a #garlic press{}). Trim and halve the @Green Beans{80%grams}(trimmed and halved).

Stir the garlic and the @Korma Curry Paste{50%grams} into the saucepan. Fry for
~{1%minute} until fragrant.

Pour the @Tomato Passata{1%carton}, @KNORR Vegetable Stock{1%pot} and
@Water for the Sauce{250%milliliter} into the saucepan. Stir in the green beans.

Bring to the boil, then simmer until the chicken is cooked through and the stew
has thickened a little, ~{8-10%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Cook so there's no pink in the middle.

When the stew has thickened slightly, stir in the @Mango Chutney{40%grams} and
@Butter{20%grams}, until melted.

Stir the roasted potatoes into the stew. Taste and season with @salt{} and
@pepper{} if needed. Add a splash of water if it's a little too thick.

Share your chicken aloo gobi stew between your #bowls{}.

Top with the roasted curried cauliflower.

Swirl the @Greek Style Natural Yoghurt{75%grams} into the stew to finish.

Enjoy!